{"data":[{"type":"questionAttempts","id":"17658936","links":{"self":"https://app.emedici.com/api/questionAttempts/17658936"},"attributes":{"position":0,"marks":1,"score":0,"answeredAt":"2025-09-30T22:58:13+09:30","options":[1],"response":null,"finalizedAt":"2025-09-30T22:58:13+09:30"},"relationships":{"user":{"data":{"type":"users","id":"50098"}},"questionSession":{"data":null},"session":{"data":null},"question":{"data":{"type":"questions","id":"20840"}},"bookmark":{"data":null}}}],"included":[{"type":"questions","id":"20840","links":{"self":"https://app.emedici.com/api/questions/20840"},"relationships":{"item":{"data":{"type":"items","id":"13715"}},"activeRevision":{"data":{"type":"questionRevisions","id":"96399"}}}},{"type":"items","id":"13715","links":{"self":"https://app.emedici.com/api/items/13715"},"attributes":{"contentType":"question"},"relationships":{"content":{"data":{"type":"questions","id":"20840"}},"activeRevision":{"data":{"type":"itemRevisions","id":"79048"}},"tags":{"data":[{"type":"tags","id":"67"},{"type":"tags","id":"11597"},{"type":"tags","id":"12331"},{"type":"tags","id":"12664"},{"type":"tags","id":"12795"}]},"contributions":{"data":[{"type":"contributions","id":"33022"},{"type":"contributions","id":"33023"}]}},"meta":{"canRevise":false,"canManage":false,"canDelete":false}},{"type":"questionRevisions","id":"96399","links":{"self":"https://app.emedici.com/api/questionRevisions/96399"},"attributes":{"stem":"\u003Cp\u003E\u003C/p\u003E","stemQuestion":"Which one of the following best describes how receptor tyrosine kinases contribute to oncogenesis?","responseType":"sba","marks":1,"options":["They become constitutively active through various genetic alterations","They exclusively promote cell cycle arrest in cancer cells","They primarily inhibit tumor suppressor gene function","They require continuous growth factor binding for oncogenic activity","They exclusively function through autocrine signaling loops"],"correctOptions":[0],"correctResponses":null,"explanation":"\u003Cp\u003EThe correct answer is that receptor tyrosine kinases \u003Cstrong\u003Ebecome constitutively active through various genetic alterations\u003C/strong\u003E. Receptor tyrosine kinases can be activated in tumors by multiple mechanisms including point mutations, gene rearrangements, and gene amplifications. These alterations lead to constitutive, growth factor-independent tyrosine kinase activity, allowing the mutant receptors to deliver mitogenic signals continuously even in the absence of growth factor stimulation.\u003C/p\u003E\u003Cp\u003EExamples include:\u003C/p\u003E\u003Cul\u003E\u003Cli\u003EPoint mutations in \u003Cem\u003EERBB1\u003C/em\u003E (encoding EGFR) in lung adenocarcinomas\u003C/li\u003E\u003Cli\u003EAmplification of \u003Cem\u003EERBB2\u003C/em\u003E (encoding HER2) in breast carcinomas\u003C/li\u003E\u003Cli\u003EGene rearrangements such as \u003Cem\u003EEML4-ALK\u003C/em\u003E fusion in lung adenocarcinomas\u003C/li\u003E\u003C/ul\u003E\u003Cp\u003EThe incorrect options can be explained as follows:\u003C/p\u003E\u003Cul\u003E\u003Cli\u003E\u003Cstrong\u003EThey exclusively function through autocrine signaling loops\u003C/strong\u003E - While some cancer cells do establish autocrine loops (producing both growth factors and their receptors), this is not the only or primary mechanism by which receptor tyrosine kinases contribute to oncogenesis.\u003C/li\u003E\u003Cli\u003E\u003Cstrong\u003EThey primarily inhibit tumor suppressor gene function\u003C/strong\u003E - Receptor tyrosine kinases promote oncogenesis through constitutive activation of growth-promoting pathways, not primarily through inhibition of tumor suppressors.\u003C/li\u003E\u003Cli\u003E\u003Cstrong\u003EThey exclusively promote cell cycle arrest in cancer cells\u003C/strong\u003E - This is incorrect as receptor tyrosine kinases promote cell proliferation, not cell cycle arrest.\u003C/li\u003E\u003Cli\u003E\u003Cstrong\u003EThey require continuous growth factor binding for oncogenic activity\u003C/strong\u003E - The oncogenic versions of receptor tyrosine kinases are constitutively active and do not require growth factor binding to signal.\u003C/li\u003E\u003C/ul\u003E","optionExplanations":["","","","",""],"learningPoints":["Oncoproteins are constitutively active proteins that participate in signaling pathways driving cell proliferation.","Receptor tyrosine kinases can be constitutively activated in tumors through point mutations, gene rearrangements, and gene amplifications.","Oncogenic growth factor receptors deliver continuous mitogenic signals to cells even in the absence of growth factors."],"references":["Kumar V, Abbas AK, Aster JC. Robbins and Cotran Pathologic Basis of Disease. 10th ed. Philadelphia: Elsevier; 2020. Chapter 7; pages 286-290."]},"relationships":{"itemRevision":{"data":{"type":"itemRevisions","id":"79048"}},"question":{"data":{"type":"questions","id":"20840"}},"stemMedia":{"data":[]},"explanationMedia":{"data":[]}}},{"type":"itemRevisions","id":"79048","links":{"self":"https://app.emedici.com/api/itemRevisions/79048"},"attributes":{"createdAt":"2025-04-01T11:10:47+10:30","updatedAt":"2025-04-01T11:11:20+10:30"},"relationships":{"item":{"data":{"type":"items","id":"13715"}},"content":{"data":{"type":"questionRevisions","id":"96399"}}},"meta":{"canDelete":false}},{"type":"tags","id":"67","links":{"self":"https://app.emedici.com/api/tags/67"},"attributes":{"emoji":"","name":"Basic Science","synonyms":null,"description":null,"position":null,"createdAt":null,"updatedAt":null},"relationships":{"group":{"data":{"type":"tagGroups","id":"5"}},"heading":{"data":null}},"meta":{"itemCount":0}},{"type":"tags","id":"11597","links":{"self":"https://app.emedici.com/api/tags/11597"},"attributes":{"emoji":"","name":"Neoplasia","synonyms":[],"description":null,"position":6,"createdAt":"2025-02-26T20:57:41+10:30","updatedAt":"2025-02-26T20:57:41+10:30"},"relationships":{"group":{"data":{"type":"tagGroups","i